-- Apex Advantage — DPE Question Bank Expansion, Batch 4 of 4 (v13)
--
-- Closes out the expansion started in v10 (72 -> 122 -> 172 -> 222).
-- This batch adds the last Aircraft Systems question (+1, completing
-- 25), all remaining Aeronautical Decision-Making & Risk Management
-- questions (+30, completing 40), and 3 Cross-Country Planning
-- questions that were short of the original +17 target from batch 2
-- (v11 only added +14, landing at 22 instead of 25 -- caught during
-- the final full-bank count check below, fixed here rather than left
-- short) -- bringing the bank to its full 256-question target.
--
-- Final category counts after this batch:
--   eligibility        20   airspace           30
--   airworthiness       20   weather            30
--   privileges          30   performance        20
--   crosscountry        25   aeromedical         8  (unchanged)
--   emergency            8  (unchanged)          aircraft-systems   25
--   adm                 40
--   ------------------------------------------------
--   TOTAL              256
--
-- The ADM questions draw on standard FAA risk-management material --
-- the DECIDE model, the risk-assessment matrix, the five hazardous
-- attitudes and their antidotes, and named cognitive biases (anchoring,
-- confirmation bias, plan continuation bias, risk homeostasis) --
-- since these are exactly the kind of concepts DPEs weave through an
-- oral exam without a dedicated "ADM section" existing on paper.
--
-- Checked against the existing 72, the 172 from v10/v11/v12, and the
-- free "10 Questions DPEs Love to Ask" guide for topical overlap.
--
-- Run this in the Supabase SQL editor, after supabase-portal-schema-v12.

insert into public.dpe_questions (id, category, question, model_answer, common_mistakes, dpe_evaluating, acs_reference, real_world_application, is_scenario, scenario_order, sort_order) values

  -- ═══════════════════ AIRCRAFT SYSTEMS, completing to 25 (+1) ═══════════════════
  ('acsys-25', 'aircraft-systems', 'What is the purpose of an alternate air source on a fuel-injected engine, and when would you actually need to use it?', 'An alternate air source provides an unfiltered, or differently filtered, air path into the induction system if the normal induction air filter or intake becomes blocked, such as by ice; if you notice a loss of engine power or manifold pressure consistent with induction blockage, especially in visible moisture near freezing temperatures, selecting alternate air routes around the blockage and should restore normal engine operation.', 'Assuming fuel-injected engines have no induction icing vulnerability at all, or not knowing the alternate air system exists as the specific remedy for this aircraft type.', 'Whether you know this system exists and its specific trigger condition, since it''s a commonly overlooked counterpart to carburetor heat on carbureted engines.', 'Area of Operation I, Task G — Operation of Systems (Knowledge and Risk Management).', 'Recognizing induction blockage and knowing your specific aircraft''s remedy, alternate air or carb heat, is what actually restores power rather than continuing to trouble-shoot the wrong system.', true, null, 24),

  -- ═══════════════════ CROSS-COUNTRY PLANNING, true-up to 25 (+3) ═══════════════════
  ('xc-23', 'crosscountry', 'You''re planning a multi-leg cross-country with three fuel stops. How does your weight and balance calculation need to change across the legs as fuel burns down and you make stops?', 'Recalculate weight and balance for each leg separately, not just once at the start of the trip, since fuel burn shifts CG, often forward as wing tanks empty, and any change in occupants or cargo at each stop directly changes both weight and CG. Confirm each leg independently falls within limits rather than assuming a single calculation at departure covers the entire multi-leg trip.', 'Doing one weight and balance calculation for the first leg and assuming it remains valid for every subsequent leg regardless of fuel burn or stops.', 'Whether you treat weight and balance as a per-leg requirement on a multi-stop trip, not a one-time preflight task.', 'Area of Operation I, Task D — Cross-Country Flight Planning (Knowledge and Risk Management).', 'A multi-leg trip with different loading at each stop genuinely needs a fresh weight and balance check each time, not a single calculation carried forward from departure.', true, null, 22),
  ('xc-24', 'crosscountry', 'You''re planning a cross-country that crosses two time zones. What practical step do most pilots take to avoid confusion in their flight planning and logs?', 'Use Coordinated Universal Time, often called Zulu time, consistently throughout flight planning, weather briefings, and navigation logs, rather than switching between local time zones as you cross them, since this avoids a real planning or timing error caused by an unnoticed time zone change partway through the trip.', 'Planning departure and arrival times in local time for each leg without converting to a single, consistent time reference, risking a scheduling or briefing-validity error at a time zone boundary.', 'Whether you have an actual practical habit for avoiding this specific, easy-to-overlook planning error.', 'Area of Operation I, Task D — Cross-Country Flight Planning (Knowledge).', 'Weather products and NOTAMs are typically issued in Zulu time specifically to avoid this exact confusion — planning in local time across a time zone change reintroduces the very error the system is designed to prevent.', false, null, 23),
  ('xc-25', 'crosscountry', 'Beyond simply being open and nearby, what makes an airport a genuinely good choice as an enroute alternate when you''re planning a cross-country?', 'A good alternate has services and facilities appropriate to a potential diversion — sufficient runway length and surface for your aircraft, fuel availability, and ideally an instrument approach if weather is a possible factor — combined with being reasonably positioned relative to your route so it''s actually reachable given fuel and weather conditions at the point you''d need to divert.', 'Picking an alternate based only on proximity on the chart, without confirming it actually has fuel, adequate runway, or services that make it a genuinely usable diversion option.', 'Whether you evaluate alternates on real operational suitability, not just geographic convenience.', 'Area of Operation I, Task D — Cross-Country Flight Planning (Knowledge and Risk Management).', 'Discovering your planned alternate has no fuel or an unusable runway only after you''ve diverted there is a real, avoidable planning failure.', false, null, 24),

  -- ═══════════════════ ADM & RISK MANAGEMENT, completing to 40 (+30) ═══════════════════
  ('adm-11', 'adm', 'What does the DECIDE model stand for, and how would you actually apply it to a real in-flight problem, such as noticing falling oil pressure?', 'DECIDE stands for Detect a change needing attention, Estimate the need to counter or respond, Choose a desirable outcome, Identify actions to successfully control the change, Do the necessary action, and Evaluate the effect of the action. Applied to falling oil pressure: detect the abnormal reading, estimate that continued flight risks engine failure, choose the outcome of a safe precautionary landing, identify the nearest suitable airport and reduced-power procedure, execute it, and evaluate whether the pressure stabilizes or continues to confirm your assessment.', 'Reciting the acronym without being able to walk through a concrete example applying each step to an actual in-flight problem.', 'Whether you can actually operate the model in real time on a specific scenario, not just recall what the letters stand for.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'A memorized model is only useful if you can actually run it under pressure — being able to walk through a real example is what separates recall from usable skill.', true, null, 10),
  ('adm-12', 'adm', 'What is a risk assessment matrix, and how do severity and likelihood combine to determine whether a specific risk is acceptable?', 'A risk assessment matrix plots the severity of a potential outcome, from negligible to catastrophic, against the likelihood of it occurring, from improbable to frequent, producing a combined risk level for a given hazard. A low-likelihood but catastrophic-severity risk, or a frequent but minor-severity risk, might both land in a similar overall risk category, even though the individual factors look very different — the combination, not either factor alone, is what determines whether the risk is acceptable.', 'Judging a risk based only on severity or only on likelihood in isolation, rather than considering how the two combine.', 'Whether you understand risk as a genuine two-dimensional assessment, not a single intuitive "how scared should I be" judgment.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'Many operators formalize this exact matrix for flight-risk assessment — even informally, thinking in both dimensions produces a more defensible go/no-go decision than gut feeling alone.', false, null, 11),
  ('adm-13', 'adm', 'What is the "chain of errors" concept in accident analysis, and why does knowing about it change how you think about a single mistake during your own flight?', 'Most accidents result not from one single catastrophic error but from a chain of smaller errors or oversights that each individually might have been survivable, but which combine to produce a bad outcome; breaking any single link in that chain — catching one of the smaller errors and correcting it — is often enough to prevent the accident entirely.', 'Treating a single mistake in isolation as either harmless or as an inevitable step toward disaster, rather than recognizing it as one link you can still break.', 'Whether you understand that catching and correcting even one error in an unfolding chain is genuinely protective, not just noting that "chains of errors" exist as a concept.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'Recognizing you''ve just made one error in a developing chain, and actively deciding to stop and reassess rather than pressing on, is real, applied risk management in the moment.', true, null, 12),
  ('adm-14', 'adm', 'What is confirmation bias, and how might it show up during a preflight weather briefing when you''re already hoping to make a specific trip?', 'Confirmation bias is the tendency to notice and weight information that supports what you already want to believe, while discounting or overlooking information that contradicts it; during a weather briefing, a pilot hoping to fly might latch onto an optimistic detail, like a brief window of improving visibility, while mentally minimizing a less convenient detail, like a SIGMET along the route, because it conflicts with the trip they already want to make.', 'Assuming bias only affects careless or inexperienced pilots, rather than recognizing it as a normal cognitive tendency that affects careful, experienced pilots too when they already want a specific outcome.', 'Whether you recognize this bias as something you personally are susceptible to, not just an abstract concept that applies to other people.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'A pilot who already wants to go is the pilot most at risk of unconsciously cherry-picking a briefing — naming this bias in yourself is a real defense against it.', true, null, 13),
  ('adm-15', 'adm', 'What is plan continuation bias, and how is it different from simple "get-there-itis"?', 'Plan continuation bias is the tendency to continue with an original plan even as conditions change and new information suggests the plan should be revised, driven partly by the mental and logistical investment already made in that plan — distinct from get-there-itis, which is specifically about external pressure to arrive on schedule. Plan continuation bias can persist even without any real external deadline, purely because switching plans feels like a loss after you''ve already committed mentally and practically to the original one.', 'Treating plan continuation bias and get-there-itis as the same thing, missing that plan continuation bias can operate even when there''s no real schedule pressure at all.', 'Whether you know these are distinct psychological mechanisms, since a pilot can be vulnerable to one without necessarily feeling classic "get-there-itis" pressure.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'Recognizing plan continuation bias explains why pilots sometimes continue a flight that''s clearly deteriorating even with no one waiting for them and no real schedule at stake.', false, null, 14),
  ('adm-16', 'adm', 'What is "scud running," and why is it considered one of the more dangerous patterns of VFR flying, even for an experienced pilot?', 'Scud running is continuing VFR flight at low altitude beneath a lowering ceiling, trying to remain in visual conditions by descending and maneuvering around terrain and obstacles as the weather deteriorates. It''s dangerous because it combines reduced altitude margin above terrain and obstacles with reduced visibility and ceiling, and because each individual descent or maneuver can feel like a small, reasonable adjustment even as the cumulative situation becomes genuinely unsafe.', 'Assuming scud running is only a risk for low-time or poorly trained pilots, rather than recognizing it as a gradual, almost imperceptible slide that can trap even experienced pilots.', 'Whether you recognize this specific, named pattern and its incremental nature, not just that "flying in bad weather is dangerous" in general.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'VFR-into-deteriorating-weather accidents are frequently the end result of exactly this pattern — a series of individually small descents that collectively become an unrecoverable situation.', false, null, 15),
  ('adm-17', 'adm', 'Continued VFR flight into instrument meteorological conditions is one of general aviation''s most consistently fatal accident categories. Why does experience alone not fully protect a pilot from it?', 'Experience helps with recognizing deteriorating conditions and flying skill, but this accident category is driven as much by decision-making and psychological factors — plan continuation bias, reluctance to turn back, overconfidence in one''s own ability to handle marginal conditions — as by raw flying skill, and those decision-making vulnerabilities don''t automatically disappear as a pilot accumulates hours.', 'Assuming more experienced or higher-time pilots are essentially immune to this accident category, when accident data shows experienced pilots represented among these accidents too.', 'Whether you understand this as fundamentally a decision-making risk, not purely a stick-and-rudder skill gap that experience alone resolves.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'Believing "this won''t happen to me because I''m experienced enough" is itself a documented contributing factor in this exact accident category.', false, null, 16),
  ('adm-18', 'adm', 'You''re taught a specific weather-minimums personal limit by your instructor, but a more experienced pilot at the airport tells you that rule is overly cautious and you should trust your own judgment instead. You go anyway, against your own trained limit. What hazardous attitude does this reflect, and what''s the antidote?', 'This reflects the anti-authority hazardous attitude — resisting or dismissing rules, guidance, or established limits because you resent being told what to do, even when that guidance exists for good reason. The antidote is recognizing that rules and personal minimums are usually there for a reason, and following them is a decision you''re making, not a limitation imposed on you against your will.', 'Not recognizing dismissing established guidance as a specific, named hazardous attitude, treating it instead as simple independent thinking.', 'Whether you can identify this specific hazardous attitude in a concrete scenario and state its actual antidote, not just its name.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'Personal minimums and training guidance exist precisely because they''re set in a calm state before pressure arrives — dismissing them under a peer''s influence removes exactly the protection they were designed to provide.', true, null, 17),
  ('adm-19', 'adm', 'You notice a minor issue during preflight, and without really thinking it through, you decide the fastest fix is to skip that checklist item entirely rather than address it properly. What hazardous attitude does this reflect, and what''s the antidote?', 'This reflects impulsivity — acting on the first thought that comes to mind without actually thinking it through, driven by a need to do something, anything, quickly. The antidote is deliberately slowing down: "not so fast, think first" before acting on the first available option.', 'Confusing genuine impulsivity with simply being decisive or efficient, rather than recognizing the specific pattern of acting before actually reasoning through the options.', 'Whether you can identify this attitude and its antidote in a concrete scenario, not just recite hazardous attitudes as an abstract list.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'A rushed, unreasoned fix to a preflight discrepancy is exactly how a small, catchable issue turns into an in-flight problem that a moment of actual thought would have prevented.', true, null, 18),
  ('adm-20', 'adm', 'You hear about another pilot having an accident in conditions similar to what you''re planning to fly today, and your reaction is that it simply wouldn''t happen to you because you''re a more careful pilot. What hazardous attitude does this reflect, and what''s the antidote?', 'This reflects invulnerability — the belief that accidents happen to other people, not to you personally. The antidote is genuinely internalizing "it could happen to me," using someone else''s accident as real, applicable information about your own risk rather than something that only proves your own superior skill or caution.', 'Treating this attitude as harmless confidence rather than recognizing it as a specific, named barrier to actually learning from someone else''s accident.', 'Whether you recognize this attitude in yourself specifically, since it''s often invisible to the person experiencing it.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'Dismissing another pilot''s accident as something that "wouldn''t happen to me" wastes a real, free lesson that could otherwise inform your own actual risk assessment today.', true, null, 19),
  ('adm-21', 'adm', 'You''re flying with a passenger who comments that the conditions look a little rough, and your response is to fly it more aggressively than you normally would to prove there''s nothing to worry about. What hazardous attitude does this reflect, and what''s the antidote?', 'This reflects the macho attitude — trying to prove something, to yourself or to others, through unnecessary risk-taking, often specifically triggered by an audience. The antidote is recognizing that "taking chances is foolish," and that flying more conservatively, not more aggressively, is what actually demonstrates good judgment.', 'Assuming this attitude only shows up as literal bragging, missing that it can appear as subtly flying more aggressively than you normally would specifically because someone is watching or questioning you.', 'Whether you recognize this attitude even in its subtler forms, not just its most obvious, stereotypical version.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'A passenger''s comment shouldn''t change your actual risk tolerance for a flight — if anything, an audience is exactly when this hazardous attitude is most likely to show up unnoticed.', true, null, 20),
  ('adm-22', 'adm', 'Partway through a flight that''s going poorly, you find yourself thinking there''s nothing you can really do about it now except hope it works out. What hazardous attitude does this reflect, and what''s the antidote?', 'This reflects resignation — believing you have little or no control over what happens, so there''s no point in trying to actively manage the situation. The antidote is recognizing "I''m not helpless, I can make a difference" — actively working the problem, since a pilot who has given up on influencing the outcome stops taking the very actions that could actually change it.', 'Confusing genuine resignation with a calm, checklist-driven response to an emergency, when resignation specifically means giving up on actively influencing the outcome at all.', 'Whether you recognize this attitude as fundamentally about disengaging from active problem-solving, not just a general description of feeling stressed.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'A pilot who mentally checks out and stops actively working a developing problem removes their own best chance of changing the outcome, exactly when active effort matters most.', true, null, 21),
  ('adm-23', 'adm', 'What is anchoring bias, and how might it affect a pilot''s in-flight troubleshooting if their very first guess about a problem turns out to be wrong?', 'Anchoring bias is the tendency to rely too heavily on the first piece of information encountered, using it as a reference point that''s hard to move away from even when new evidence suggests it''s wrong. In troubleshooting, a pilot who first suspects one cause for a problem may keep interpreting subsequent evidence through that initial guess, delaying recognition of the actual cause even as better information becomes available.', 'Assuming a wrong initial diagnosis is a simple, one-time mistake, without recognizing the ongoing bias that makes it hard to abandon even as contrary evidence accumulates.', 'Whether you understand this as an active, ongoing bias affecting how you interpret new information, not just a single incorrect guess.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'Real in-flight troubleshooting benefits from actively re-evaluating your first guess as new symptoms appear, rather than forcing every new piece of evidence to fit your original theory.', false, null, 22),
  ('adm-24', 'adm', 'What is the "halo effect," and how might it lead a pilot to trust their own judgment in an area where they actually have little real experience?', 'The halo effect is the tendency to let a positive impression in one area — such as being a skilled, confident stick-and-rudder pilot — create unearned confidence or trust in a completely different area, such as weather judgment or navigation planning, where that skill doesn''t actually transfer. A pilot might assume that because they''re excellent at handling the airplane, their weather decision-making must be equally sound, even without evidence that it actually is.', 'Assuming general skill or confidence in one area of flying automatically extends to competence in an unrelated area, without evidence specific to that area.', 'Whether you can recognize when confidence in one skill is being unjustifiably extended to a different, untested one.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'Being a smooth, confident pilot in the pattern says nothing about your actual weather judgment — conflating the two is a real, documented way pilots overestimate their readiness for a specific flight.', false, null, 23),
  ('adm-25', 'adm', 'You''re interrupted partway through your before-takeoff checklist by a radio call. What''s the risk in how you resume the checklist afterward, and what''s the safest practice?', 'The risk is resuming from memory at roughly where you think you left off, potentially skipping an item near the interruption point; the safer practice is going back to the beginning of that checklist section, or at minimum a clearly marked earlier point, and running through it again rather than trusting your memory of exactly where you stopped.', 'Assuming you can reliably remember the exact point of interruption and simply continuing from there, rather than restarting from a safely early point in the checklist.', 'Whether you have an actual, safe practice for interruption recovery, not just an assumption that you''ll remember correctly.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'Interrupted checklists are a well-documented, real cause of missed items — takeoff configuration accidents in particular have been traced to exactly this kind of interruption.', true, null, 24),
  ('adm-26', 'adm', 'What is the "startle response," and how does chair-flying or scenario-based training actually help reduce its effect during a real emergency?', 'The startle response is the brief physiological and cognitive disruption — elevated heart rate, tunnel vision, delayed processing — that occurs when something sudden and unexpected happens, which can delay a pilot''s ability to begin an appropriate response. Chair-flying and scenario-based training help by making the initial response pattern familiar and rehearsed in advance, so the brain has something practiced to fall back on rather than needing to reason through the entire response from scratch while still startled.', 'Assuming startle only affects undertrained or inexperienced pilots, or not connecting mental rehearsal specifically to reducing this initial reaction-time delay.', 'Whether you understand why rehearsal specifically helps with the startle response, not just that "practice is generally good."', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'The first few seconds after a genuine surprise, like an unexpected engine roughness, are exactly where rehearsed, chair-flown responses pay off the most.', false, null, 25),
  ('adm-27', 'adm', 'You''ve become accustomed to using a GPS moving map for nearly all your navigation. What risk does that create, and how do you guard against it?', 'Heavy reliance on a moving map can erode basic pilotage, dead reckoning, and general positional-awareness skills over time, since the automation is doing work you''d otherwise be doing yourself; guard against this by periodically practicing manual navigation methods, maintaining a genuine mental picture of your position independent of the display, and treating the GPS as an aid to cross-check against, not a replacement for basic navigation awareness.', 'Assuming GPS reliability itself is the only risk, missing that the real risk is the pilot''s own atrophied skill and awareness if the automation were to fail or be wrong.', 'Whether you recognize automation dependency as a skill-erosion risk in yourself, not just an equipment-reliability question.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'A GPS failure or database error is manageable if your underlying navigation skill and situational awareness haven''t atrophied — that''s only true if you''ve actually kept those skills exercised.', false, null, 26),
  ('adm-28', 'adm', 'What is the "Swiss cheese model" of accident causation, and how does it explain why a single organizational or procedural weakness doesn''t usually cause an accident by itself?', 'The Swiss cheese model represents each layer of defense — training, procedures, equipment, individual judgment — as a slice of cheese with holes representing that layer''s specific weaknesses; an accident generally requires the holes in multiple layers to align at the same moment, letting a hazard pass through every layer of defense at once, rather than any single layer''s weakness being sufficient on its own.', 'Assuming a single procedural gap or individual mistake is sufficient by itself to explain most accidents, rather than recognizing that multiple layers of defense usually have to fail together.', 'Whether you understand this as a systems-level model, useful for recognizing that improving even one layer reduces overall risk even if other weaknesses remain.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'This model is exactly why redundant layers of defense — checklists, personal minimums, and good judgment together — matter more than any single one alone.', false, null, 27),
  ('adm-29', 'adm', 'How does time pressure specifically degrade decision-making quality, separate from the specific hazard of get-there-itis?', 'Time pressure narrows the range of options a person actually considers, favors the first available or most familiar option over a more thorough comparison, and reduces the mental bandwidth available for double-checking assumptions — this happens even without a specific external deadline driving it, simply because less available time compresses the decision process itself.', 'Treating time pressure and get-there-itis as identical, rather than recognizing time pressure as a more general cognitive effect that degrades decisions even absent a specific desire to "get there."', 'Whether you understand the general cognitive mechanism, not just the specific, named get-there-itis hazard.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'Recognizing that compressed decision time itself degrades quality — regardless of the specific reason for the time pressure — is why deliberately slowing down in a rushed moment is a genuine, general risk-management practice.', false, null, 28),
  ('adm-30', 'adm', 'You''re flying with a more experienced, higher-time pilot friend in the right seat as a passenger, and they suggest a course of action you''re not fully comfortable with. How do you handle this while remaining PIC?', 'As PIC, the authority and responsibility for the flight remain yours regardless of the other person''s experience level or certificate; acknowledge their input respectfully, but make your own decision based on your own risk assessment, and don''t defer simply because they have more hours or a stronger personality in the cabin.', 'Deferring to a passenger''s suggestion purely because of their greater experience or more assertive personality, rather than making the actual PIC decision yourself.', 'Whether you''d maintain genuine PIC authority under real interpersonal pressure from someone more experienced than you, not just textbook pressure.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'The person in the left seat is legally and practically responsible for the flight regardless of who else is on board — a steep cockpit gradient toward a more experienced passenger is a real, documented risk factor.', true, null, 29),
  ('adm-31', 'adm', 'Once you''ve identified a specific hazard for an upcoming flight, what are the general categories of response available to you, beyond simply deciding to go or not go?', 'Options generally include eliminating the risk entirely, such as by changing the route or timing to remove the hazard altogether; mitigating it, such as by adding a fuel stop, choosing a different altitude, or bringing additional equipment to reduce its severity or likelihood; and accepting it as-is if it''s already within an acceptable level, while continuing to monitor it in case it changes.', 'Treating every identified hazard as a binary go/no-go decision, without considering that many risks can actually be reduced through mitigation rather than requiring outright avoidance.', 'Whether you know these are distinct, real categories of response, giving you more actual options than a simple yes-or-no framing.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'Many flights that would otherwise be a hard "no" become reasonable once you actively mitigate the specific hazard, rather than treating every risk as something you either accept whole or refuse entirely.', false, null, 30),
  ('adm-32', 'adm', 'What is a personal minimums checklist, and why is writing it down in advance more effective than simply having a general sense of your own limits?', 'A personal minimums checklist is a specific, written set of limits for weather, currency, fatigue, and other risk factors that you commit to before you''re actually facing a real decision, under no pressure; writing it down in advance is more effective than a general sense of your limits because it removes the temptation to rationalize an exception in the moment, when pressure and motivation to fly are actually present.', 'Relying on a vague, unwritten sense of "I know my own limits" rather than a specific, written commitment made in a calm state ahead of time.', 'Whether you''ve actually done this exercise, or would, rather than just agreeing with the concept in the abstract.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'A specific number written down last week is much harder to rationalize away than a vague feeling you''re having right now, standing next to the airplane, wanting to go.', false, null, 31),
  ('adm-33', 'adm', 'What is the difference between being "current" and being "proficient," and why might a pilot who is legally current for a flight still not be ready for it?', 'Currency refers to meeting the specific, minimum regulatory recency requirements, such as three takeoffs and landings in the preceding 90 days; proficiency refers to your actual, practical skill level for the specific flight you''re planning, which can be meaningfully lower than the legal minimum suggests, especially after a long layoff, in unfamiliar conditions, or in an aircraft you haven''t flown much recently. A pilot can be fully legal to fly and still not be genuinely ready for a specific flight''s actual demands.', 'Treating legal currency as equivalent to actual readiness, rather than recognizing that meeting a regulatory minimum doesn''t guarantee genuine proficiency for a specific flight.', 'Whether you can honestly self-assess proficiency separately from the lower bar of legal currency.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'A pilot who is current but not truly proficient for a specific flight''s demands, such as a crosswind landing after a long layoff, should treat that gap as a real risk factor, not a technicality.', false, null, 32),
  ('adm-34', 'adm', 'Many pilots hesitate to actually use the word "emergency" over the radio even when something is genuinely going wrong. Why does this hesitation happen, and what should actually drive the decision to declare?', 'Pilots often hesitate due to concern about paperwork, embarrassment, or being perceived as overreacting, even when the situation genuinely warrants extra attention and resources; the decision to declare should be driven purely by whether you need priority handling, additional assistance, or want ATC actively tracking your situation, not by social or administrative concerns, since a declared emergency carries no automatic penalty and exists specifically to get you help.', 'Delaying a declaration out of concern for how it will look or what paperwork might follow, rather than basing the decision purely on whether you actually need the added attention and resources.', 'Whether you''d actually declare when warranted despite the social hesitation, not just know intellectually that you''re allowed to.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'Hesitating to declare an emergency out of embarrassment has genuinely delayed help reaching pilots who needed it — the paperwork concern is a real psychological barrier worth naming and overriding.', true, null, 33),
  ('adm-35', 'adm', 'You have a talkative passenger who wants to chat throughout the flight, including during your descent and approach into a busy airport. How do you manage this?', 'Politely let your passenger know before the flight, or at the start of the descent, that you''ll need quiet focus during the busier phases like descent, approach, and landing, and that you''ll be happy to talk more once established in cruise or after landing; treating critical phases of flight as requiring your full attention, with minimal non-essential conversation, protects your situational awareness exactly when task load is highest.', 'Allowing a passenger''s conversation to continue uninterrupted through a high-workload phase out of politeness, rather than proactively setting the expectation in advance.', 'Whether you''d proactively manage this distraction risk rather than passively tolerating it out of social politeness.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'This informal version of the "sterile cockpit" discipline used in professional operations protects exactly the phases of flight — approach and landing — where distraction-related accidents most often occur.', true, null, 34),
  ('adm-36', 'adm', 'You notice the engine running slightly rough and become intensely focused on diagnosing the exact cause, checking gauges and switching tanks repeatedly. A few minutes later you realize your altitude has drifted down significantly and your heading has wandered. What happened, and how do you prevent it?', 'This is fixation — becoming so intensely focused on one problem that overall aircraft control and situational awareness suffer, even though "aviate first" is the correct priority. Prevent it by consciously returning attention to basic aircraft control and a scan of primary instruments at intervals while troubleshooting, rather than letting a secondary problem fully absorb your attention for an extended, uninterrupted period.', 'Treating full absorption in a technical problem as appropriately thorough troubleshooting, rather than recognizing it as a loss of the basic aviate-first priority.', 'Whether you recognize fixation as a specific, named hazard, and would build in a habit of returning to basic aircraft control during troubleshooting rather than losing track of it.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'Fixation on a secondary problem while losing basic aircraft control has caused real accidents where the original problem was actually minor and survivable on its own.', true, null, 35),
  ('adm-37', 'adm', 'ADM and risk management don''t have one dedicated section on the actual oral exam the way weather or airspace do. So how should you expect a DPE to actually test this material during your checkride?', 'A DPE typically weaves ADM and risk-management questions through every other topic rather than asking them in isolation — for example, asking not just what the weather minimums are, but what you''d actually do given a specific, marginal weather scenario, or not just what a regulation says, but how you''d handle a specific situation testing your judgment under that regulation. Expect judgment-testing follow-up questions attached to nearly every technical topic, not a standalone ADM quiz.', 'Preparing for ADM only as an isolated topic to study in one dedicated session, rather than expecting it woven through every other subject area during the actual exam.', 'Whether you understand how the exam is actually structured, since this changes how you should practice — thinking through scenarios across every topic, not memorizing an ADM section in isolation.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'Preparing by practicing judgment calls attached to weather, airspace, systems, and every other topic is genuinely more representative of the real exam than treating ADM as its own separate study block.', false, null, 36),
  ('adm-38', 'adm', 'What is risk homeostasis, and how might installing a new safety feature, such as an angle-of-attack indicator or ADS-B traffic display, unintentionally lead a pilot to accept more risk elsewhere?', 'Risk homeostasis is the tendency for a person to unconsciously adjust their behavior to maintain a roughly constant, personally acceptable level of overall risk — so that adding a genuine safety improvement in one area can lead to quietly accepting more risk in another area, such as flying in worse weather because you now have better traffic awareness, offsetting some or all of the actual safety benefit the new equipment was supposed to provide.', 'Assuming a new safety feature automatically produces a net safety improvement, without considering whether your own risk tolerance might quietly shift to offset it.', 'Whether you''re aware of this specific tendency in yourself, since it''s a genuinely counterintuitive, easy-to-miss effect.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'A pilot who buys better equipment but doesn''t consciously guard against risk homeostasis may end up no safer overall, simply shifting risk from one area to another.', false, null, 37),
  ('adm-39', 'adm', 'You''re on the third leg of a long flying day. You haven''t violated any specific rest requirement, since Part 91 doesn''t impose formal duty-time limits the way Part 135 or 121 operations do, but you''re personally feeling drained. How do you weigh whether to continue?', 'Since there''s no regulatory duty-time limit to lean on for a Part 91 flight, the decision rests entirely on your own honest fatigue self-assessment, separate from and in addition to any single night''s sleep — cumulative fatigue across a long day is real even without any specific rule being violated. Treat your own subjective but honest assessment as the actual limiting factor, since no external rule will stop you if you don''t stop yourself.', 'Treating the absence of a formal duty-time regulation as evidence that continuing must be fine, rather than recognizing that Part 91 deliberately leaves this entirely to the pilot''s own judgment.', 'Whether you understand that the lack of a regulatory limit here places the entire responsibility on your own honest self-assessment, not on some rule protecting you by default.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix) / Area of Operation I, Task H — Human Factors.', 'Cumulative fatigue across a long flying day is a real, physiologically valid risk even when no single regulation has been violated — Part 91 pilots don''t have a duty-time rule protecting them by default.', true, null, 38),
  ('adm-40', 'adm', 'What is "negative transfer of training," and how might experience in a different aircraft actually work against you when transitioning to a new one?', 'Negative transfer of training occurs when a habit or reflex that worked correctly in a previous aircraft is applied incorrectly in a new one because the systems, procedures, or handling characteristics differ — for example, a habit related to fuel system management or a control response that was appropriate in one aircraft type but is actually wrong, or even hazardous, in a different type. Recognizing that experience can sometimes work against you, not just for you, is part of a genuine aircraft transition, not just learning what''s new.', 'Assuming more experience in any aircraft is uniformly protective in a new one, without considering that some specific habits may actually be wrong for the new type.', 'Whether you understand that experienced pilots face this specific transition risk too, not just low-time pilots learning something for the first time.', 'Special Emphasis Area — Aeronautical Decision-Making and Risk Management (ACS Appendix).', 'A genuinely thorough checkout in a new aircraft type specifically looks for habits that might be negative transfer, not just knowledge that''s simply new.', false, null, 39);
